A friend argued that backgammon is a traditional male game in some cultures because playing it forces you to learn to take very rapid decisions and react quickly. If you wait too long thinking it through before making a move you tend to lose often. Trains you to be more decisive.

Apparently in Europe backgammon really took off during the Crusades among the Christian armies and everyone played it to the point where they set rules that only knights are allowed to bet money on games. In old Dutch paintings you often see men who look like soldiers playing it.

There's definitely something to backgammon being a high T game if you notice which of your friends tend to be good at it. I would love to see a study linking backgammon performance to grip strength or alcohol consumption.
